notes: Baseline: PPML with full FE (cntry*sect*year + cntry*prod + prod*year), cluster(country+product). Table 2 Col 2. Coef=-3.617, SE=0.692, p<0.001, N=95905.
SE: cluster country only. Same point estimate as baseline (-3.617), SE changes to 0.693. Tests sensitivity of inference to clustering dimension.
SE: cluster product only. Same point estimate (-3.617), SE=0.505 (smaller). Product clustering yields tighter inference.
SE: cluster year only. Same point estimate (-3.617), SE=0.406. Very few clusters (13 years), inference may be unreliable.
SE: heteroskedasticity-robust (no clustering). Same point estimate (-3.617), SE=0.296. Most aggressive inference assumption.
SE: cluster country*year. Same point estimate (-3.617), SE=0.343. Alternative two-way dimension for clustering.
FE: country + product + year (separate, not interacted). Table A3 Panel A Col 1. Coef=-3.384, larger sample (N=114135). Less restrictive FE structure.
FE: country*year + product. Table A3 Panel A Col 2. Coef=-3.285, N=114011. Controls for country-specific time trends.
FE: country*year + product*year. Table A3 Panel A Col 3. Coef=-4.366, N=110910. Both time-varying country and product effects.
FE: country*year + country*product + product*year. Table A3 Panel A Col 4. Coef=-2.924, N=105479. Full bilateral FE without sector.
FE: country + year only (minimal). Coef=-0.986, p=0.273, NOT significant. Omitted variable bias without product FE -- demonstrates importance of product controls.
FE: country*product + year. Coef=-2.712, significant. Missing product*year and country*sector*year FE.
FE: product*year only. Coef=-1.871, p=0.074, marginally significant. No country-level controls; captures only cross-product variation.
FE: country*product only (no time dimension). Coef=-4.887, highly significant. All variation comes from within-pair changes over time.
OLS: ln(imports) with full FE, cluster(country+product). Table 2 Col 3 analog. Coef=-1.576. OLS drops zero trade flows and estimates a different parameter (semi-elasticity).
OLS: separate country + product + year FE. Coef=-2.843. OLS with simpler FE structure.
OLS: country*year + product*year FE. Coef=-2.837. OLS with bilateral time-varying FE.
OLS: country*year + country*product + product*year FE. Coef=-1.761. OLS with full bilateral FE.
OLS: arcsinh(imports) as DV. Coef=-1.569. Santos-Silva & Tenreyro alternative that handles zeros in OLS framework.
Treatment: LN_TARIFF_NZ (no zero-import imputations). Table 3 Col 2. Coef=-3.617, identical to baseline because same underlying data when tariff is defined. Tests sensitivity to tariff construction.
Treatment: tariff rate in levels (not log-transformed). Coef=-2.317. Tests functional form of tariff measure.
Sample: non-specific duties only. Table 3 Col 3. Coef=-5.211, larger magnitude. Ad valorem tariffs are better measured.
Sample: specific duties only. Table 3 Col 4. Coef=-2.046, p=0.026. Specific duties harder to measure as ad valorem equivalent.
Sample: biennial intervals. Table 2 Col 4. Coef=-3.653. Using every-other-year to reduce serial correlation in panel.
Sample: pre-Ottawa period (1924-1931). Coef=-2.135, p=0.002. Tests whether effect is present before Ottawa Conference.
Sample: post-Ottawa period (1932-1936). Coef=-2.839, p<0.001. Tests effect during imperial preference era.
Sample: Empire countries only. Coef=-4.525, p=0.050, marginally significant. Within-Empire tariff effects; small sample (N=14011).
Sample: non-Empire countries only. Coef=-1.005, p=0.016. Tariff effect on non-Empire trade partners is smaller.
Sample: exclude United States. FAILED (demeaning did not converge). Cannot evaluate.
Sample: exclude United Kingdom. Coef=-1.300, p<0.001. UK is the largest Empire trading partner; dropping it reduces the coefficient substantially.
Sample: top 10 trading partners only. Coef=-4.201, p<0.001. Restricting to major partners increases magnitude.
Sample: trim top 1% import values. Coef=-3.304, p<0.001. Robust to trimming outlier trade values.
Sample: trim top 5% tariff values. Coef=-5.096, p<0.001. Removing extreme tariffs increases magnitude.
Sample: drop 1924 (first year). Coef=-3.649, p<0.001. Nearly identical to baseline -- no first-year sensitivity.
Sample: drop 1936 (last year). Coef=-3.396, p<0.001. Slightly smaller without last year.
Sample: middle period (1927-1933). Coef=-2.388, p<0.001. Core years around Great Depression and Ottawa Conference.
Sample: only positive tariff observations. Coef=-4.032, p<0.001. Excludes duty-free products (LN_TARIFF=0).
Sector: Agricultural and Vegetable Products - Mainly Food. Coef=-4.771. Sector subsample with reduced FE (cntry*prod + prod*year).
Sector: Agricultural and Vegetable Products - Other. Coef=-1.541, p=0.051, marginally significant. Small sector subsample.
Sector: Animals and Animal Products. Coef=-4.428, p=0.009. Sector subsample.
Sector: Chemicals and Allied Products. Coef=-8.019, p<0.001. Very large tariff effect in chemicals.
Sector: Fibres, Textiles and Textile Products. Coef=-5.818, p=0.018. Sector subsample.
Sector: Iron and Its Products. Coef=-10.574, p<0.001. Largest sector-specific effect.
Sector: Miscellaneous Commodities. Coef=-6.227, p=0.001. Sector subsample.
Sector: Non-Ferrous Metals and Their Products. Coef=-4.606, p<0.001. Sector subsample.
Sector: Non-Metallic Minerals and Their Products. Coef=-6.604, p=0.017. Sector subsample.
Sector: Wood, Wood Products and Paper. Coef=-4.952, p=0.001. Sector subsample.
Interaction: Empire vs non-Empire tariff effect. Reports LN_TARIFF_EMPIRE coef=-4.293. Tests whether tariff effect differs by Empire membership.
Interaction: Ottawa vs non-Ottawa tariff effect. Reports ottawa_TARIFF coef=-5.247. Tests whether Ottawa agreement tariffs have different trade effects.
Controls: add tariff risk. Coef=-3.986, p<0.001, N=74008. Table 6 Col 3 style -- controlling for tariff uncertainty measure.
Controls: GDP + exchange rate. Table A4 style. Coef=-4.119. Reduced FE (cntry*prod + prod*year) to avoid collinearity with macro controls.
Controls: GDP + ER + treaty dummies. Coef=-3.708. Adding macro and institutional controls reduces magnitude slightly.
Cross-section: year 1924. FAILED (collinearity). Single-year cross-section with country*product FE is not identified.
Cross-section: year 1928. FAILED (collinearity). Same identification problem.
Cross-section: year 1932. FAILED (collinearity). Same identification problem.
Cross-section: year 1936. FAILED (collinearity). Same identification problem.
Country: United States. FAILED (collinearity). Single-country estimate with product*year FE not identified.
Country: United Kingdom. FAILED (collinearity). Same identification problem.
Country: Germany. FAILED (collinearity). Same identification problem.
Country: France. FAILED (collinearity). Same identification problem.
Outcome: winsorized imports (1st/99th percentile). Coef=-3.015, p<0.001. Tests sensitivity to extreme trade values in PPML.
OLS: cluster country only. Same OLS point estimate (-1.576) as spec 15, SE=0.245. Tests OLS inference sensitivity.
OLS: Empire subsample. Coef=-2.331, p<0.001. OLS on Empire countries only.
OLS: non-specific duties. Coef=-2.603, p<0.001. OLS on ad valorem duties subsample.
OLS: pre-Ottawa period. Coef=-1.120, p<0.001. OLS on pre-1932 subsample.
